{
  "text": "Temporal coupling of cell cycle arrest and cell differentiation appears to be universal during organismal development [CITATION_1] . Cell cycle arrest thus occurs prior to the differentiation of preadipocytes into adipocytes [CITATION_2] . The transcription factor Prospero simultaneously regulates the expression of multiple cell cycle regulatory genes and neuronal lineage developmental genes in Drosophila [CITATION_3] . The antiproliferative protein B cell translocation gene 1 (BTG1) is expressed at cell confluence as well as at the onset of myoblast differentiation, and its overexpression concurrently induces cell cycle arrest and terminal differentiation [CITATION_4] . MyoD, a skeletal muscle-specific transcriptional regulator, coordinates skeletal muscle differentiation during cell cycle arrest in the G 0 -G 1 phase by inducing the expression of the cyclin-dependent kinase (CDK)1 inhibitor p21 [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . Additionally, forced silencing of proliferative signaling stimulates the differentiation of embryonic stem cells [CITATION_7] . The precise nature of the relation between cell cycle arrest and the induction of differentiation has remained unclear, however.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "7698525",
